rComments: A real gem. Work through the literature at your own pace, but don't cram it the night before the midterm/final. Questions (Short/Long Answer) are very clear and they are structured with multiple parts (ie: Parts (a) through (e)) so that you know exactly what details are being asked for. 100% would recommend.

Enthusiastic and knowledgeable about the subject and the corresponding papers. Very willing to answer questions. Pretty lenient on marking despite only having a midterm and final. No need to go to lectures since he summarizes the required readings. But, if you fall behind on readings, you will be doomed.
teacherRatingTags: ['So many papers', 'Gives good feedback', 'Graded by few things']

rComments: Primarily bases his class/course material from review and primary literature. Some of the articles are quite difficult which is why attending lectures helps to clear up confusion. Don't be intimidated by how the course relies on scientific literature, it is still doable, and he makes the tests very fair. Solid prof.

Although this class was boring at times, I learned a lot. He sets a very laid back environment in the classroom, with lively discussion. Very helpful and approachable for the essay, and is an easy A course if you put in the effort.
teacherRatingTags: ['Accessible outside class', 'Participation matters', 'Graded by few things']

rComments: Professor Berleth knows a lot of things. His seminar presentations are a little light. However, assignments are marked very fairly. He loves engaging in conversation, so make sure to participate in class, as it may matter in respect to your grades.
